{"key":"processedPost-10235433","value":{"id":10235433,"first":10233855,"last":10250805,"when":1240757247,"utime":"04/26/09 05:47 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br />DO I cover with foil and place back in my 86 degree place for a couple days or go straight to my fruiting chamber with 12/12 light.<br /></blockquote><br /><br />You should NEVER at any time expose mycelium to temps that hot.&nbsp; That's probably why your jars are pinning invitro.<br /><br />I'd suggest pasteurizing some manure or coir, and then mix your grains into it, cover with foil until fully colonized at normal room temperature, and then remove the foil and expose to fruiting conditions.&nbsp; You can also case by laying the grains in a tray, and covering with peat/verm buffered to pH 8.&nbsp; Cover with foil for a week until about 30% of the surface is colonized, and then expose to fruiting conditions.<br /><br />Next time, don't 'incubate'.&nbsp; It causes all sorts of problems, and molds and bacteria like heat much more than mushroom mycelium, which prefers normal room temp.<br />RR","title":"Re: HELP!!!"}}